public static boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
    if (n <= 0 || (n & (n - 1)) != 0) {
        // If n is not a positive integer or is not of the form (3^x) - 1 (i.e., not a power of three), return false
        return false;
    }

    // Check if n is a power of three using bitwise AND with (n - 1) and (n + 1)
    return (n & (n - 1)) == 0 && (n & (n + 1)) != 0;
}
```

This solution checks if `n` satisfies two conditions:

- `n <= 0 || (n & (n - 1)) != 0`: `n` cannot be negative, and if it's positive, it should not have any trailing zero bits (i.e., not be of the form `(3^x) - 1`) to avoid false positives like `27` and `-1`.
- `(n & (n - 1)) == 0 && (n & (n + 1)) != 0`: `n` must be of the form `3^x` (i.e., have a single bit set) and not be equal to `(3^x) + 1`, which would imply that `x + 1` results in an odd power of three instead of an even one.

Using bit manipulation instead of loops/recursion improves performance, especially for large values of `n`, by avoiding unnecessary iterations and comparisons.

